To summarize, I tried following with openblas, but still saw performance degradation:

1. Compiling OpenBLAS from source:
	```bash
	git clone https://github.com/xianyi/OpenBLAS
	cd OpenBLAS
	make FC=gfortran
	sudo make PREFIX=/opt/openblas install
	```

2. Using released OpenBLAS:
	```bash
	sudo yum install openblas
	sudo ln -s /lib64/libopenblas.so.0 /usr/lib/libopenblas.so
	```

3. Also, commented any threading logic in systemml.cpp to rule out possibility of bug due to extension APIs:
	```python
        //if(NUM_THREADS == -1) {
        //      NUM_THREADS = openblas_get_num_threads();
        //}
        // openblas_set_num_threads(NUM_THREADS);
	```

4. Even though I was using newer Centos 7 and gcc 4.8 (both supporting avx instructions), I also tried updating binutils and reinstalling OpenBLAS as per https://github.com/xianyi/OpenBLAS/wiki/faq#binutils

My guess is that this is due to a performance bug in OpenBLAS on multi-socket machine: https://github.com/xianyi/OpenBLAS/issues/611

```bash
$ cat /proc/cpuinfo | grep "physical id" | sort -u | wc -l
2
```

Cool. Let's wait to hear back from @mboehm7  and @bertholdreinwald 

Regarding distributed implementation of convolution and max pooling, there are following options:
1. Current approach (Mini-batch training): for loop { CP conv + CP max_pool }
2. Batched approach (applicable for batched training as well as batched prediction):  for loop { SPARK conv + SPARK max_pool }
3. Parfor Prediction: remote SPARK parfor loop { CP conv + CP max_pool }

@dusenberrymw  Which case do you think we should address first ?

@mboehm7  I thought you had an issue with externalizing the decision of disabling sparse. In this PR, I was disabling sparse (not caching) only when we observe a conv2d-related script. My concern is that sparsity threshold of 0.4 is way too optimistic for allocating vectors (for example: mini-batch deep learning script). I can try other approaches to reduce the impact of this threshold (for example: https://github.com/apache/incubator-systemml/pull/329), but eventually we will have to systematically address whether the sparsity threshold of 0.4 is appropriate choice for all our algorithms (including lenet, autoencoder, lstm, etc). Until then, I can close this PR as we do not have consensus.

>> Having the static flag would affect all operations in a session; coming through MLContext, even across scripts.
That's a good point. I was not aware we decided to make MLContext multi-threaded.

Can demonstrate with:
```
import org.apache.sysml.api.mlcontext._
import org.apache.sysml.api.mlcontext.ScriptFactory._
val ml = new MLContext(sc)
val str = """
X = "howdy";
while (X == "howdy") {
    print('ok');
    X = "stop it";
}
A = matrix("1 2 3 4 5 6", rows=3, cols=2)
for (i in 1:nrow(A)) {
    print("for A[" + i + ",1]:" + as.scalar(A[i,1]))
}
if (X == "howdy") {
  print('X is howdy');
} else {
  print('X is not howdy');
}
"""
val scr = dml(str)
val rdd1 = sc.parallelize(Array("1.0,2.0", "3.0,4.0"))
scr.in("A", rdd1)
class MyScriptExecutor extends org.apache.sysml.api.mlcontext.ScriptExecutor {
  override def execute(scr:org.apache.sysml.api.mlcontext.Script):org.apache.sysml.api.mlcontext.MLResults = { setup(scr); parseScript(); return null;}
}
val se = new MyScriptExecutor
ml.execute(scr, se)
scr.getScriptExecutor.getDmlProgram
```

